more than one phonic

01:02:54.560 --> 01:02:56.280 align:middle line:90%
going on at a time.

01:02:56.280 --> 01:02:59.210 align:middle line:84%
Well, here there's more than
one rhythm going on at a time.

01:02:59.210 --> 01:03:03.250 align:middle line:84%
And it's powerfully
rhythmic democracy.

01:03:03.250 --> 01:03:05.900 align:middle line:84%
This democracy of
rhythm is something

01:03:05.900 --> 01:03:10.430 align:middle line:84%
intrinsic to not only know
African ritualistic music

01:03:10.430 --> 01:03:13.010 align:middle line:90%
but also social music.

01:03:13.010 --> 01:03:17.990 align:middle line:84%
And these rhythms
being brought across,

01:03:17.990 --> 01:03:22.700 align:middle line:84%
really fundamental to
what becomes every strain

01:03:22.700 --> 01:03:25.580 align:middle line:90%
of popular music down to today.

01:03:25.580 --> 01:03:30.880 align:middle line:84%
The for example the
bambula rhythm--

01:03:30.880 --> 01:03:33.370 align:middle line:90%
[RHYTHMIC CLAPPING]

01:03:33.370 --> 01:03:36.760 align:middle line:90%


01:03:36.760 --> 01:03:37.560 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:03:37.560 --> 01:03:39.290 align:middle line:84%
Well, you can hear
that all the way down

01:03:39.290 --> 01:03:43.180 align:middle line:84%
to the washboard players on
Royal Street this afternoon

01:03:43.180 --> 01:03:47.960 align:middle line:84%
or the lady that we met at
Sally Ann's place on Sunday

01:03:47.960 --> 01:03:51.110 align:middle line:84%
also, for a minute,
tapped into that rhythm.

01:03:51.110 --> 01:03:53.120 align:middle line:84%
Just naturally, never
having drummed before,

01:03:53.120 --> 01:03:55.415 align:middle line:90%
she played that bambula rhythm.

01:03:55.415 --> 01:03:57.380 align:middle line:84%
And I just thought
that's very interesting.

01:03:57.380 --> 01:03:59.300 align:middle line:84%
And then there are other
fundamental rhythms,

01:03:59.300 --> 01:04:03.780 align:middle line:84%
like what we call the
key in percussion,

01:04:03.780 --> 01:04:08.940 align:middle line:84%
in Afro-Yoruba
percussion is the clave.

01:04:08.940 --> 01:04:10.680 align:middle line:84%
So it's a rhythmic
pattern which I

01:04:10.680 --> 01:04:15.050 align:middle line:84%
learned is two ways,
haircut, shave, shampoo

01:04:15.050 --> 01:04:19.790 align:middle line:84%
and shave, haircut, shampoo
